 In <31hao6$fiv@eis.calstate.edu>
 wmoyes@eis.calstate.edu (William A Moyes) writes:


>        A few years back, I rember hearing alot of talk about CA's
>(Cellular Automations<sp?>) usefulness to cryptography. I have a simple
>question, are they still concidered secure, or has someone found a way to
>crack them? I am thinking of the one that used several cells in a line
>that have OR statements and addition (I think).

 The last nail in that coffin is the identification of CA's as
 LFSR's in drag:

      "It is shown that the bit sequence from a stage of a CA
      is identical to that from the LFSR found by the similarity
      transformation."  [1: 762]


 Reference

 [1]   Bardell, P.  1990.  Analysis of Cellular Automata Used as
       Pseudorandom Pattern Generators.  Proceedings of 1990
       International Test Conference.  (IEEE)  762-768.

